Author: mersaults#1657
Content: Notice that answer specifically says *amortized* time complexity. This means that in the vast majority of cases the algorithm runs in O(1) time, but very infrequently it will run in O(n)

Author: mersaults#1657
Content: Technically, the time complexity of an arbitrary array insert is O(n) since that's the worst case, but it's unnecessarily pessimistic to think of it this way. So, we use amortized analysis because it gives us a much better picture of the actual asymptotic upper bound since it's almost like taking the average over a sequence of operations

Author: mersaults#1657
Content:
E is correct but it's something that you have to intuit:

Note that an insert to an array with our implementation takes O(1) in the vast majority of cases. This means that over a sequence of n inserts you're going to have a total runtime of O(n)

Author: mersaults#1657
Content: This doesn't mean that Big O here is anything other than worst case. Despite the fact that your worst case dynamic array insert is O(n), the worst possible case over a sequence of operations is that you have a few operations which end up being O(n). Note that this is distinct because it's over a *sequence* of operations.

Author: Stea1thTornado#8402
Content: Big O is used to describe asymptotic upper bound, Big Œ© is is used to describe asymptotic lower bound, and Big Œò is used to describe kind of the average

Author: Stea1thTornado#8402
Content: so they are related, but not identical

Author: Stea1thTornado#8402
Content: in not technical terms, big O is worst case, big Œ© is best case, and big Œò is average

Author: gcevans#8805
Content: Actually worst or not is orthogonal in general. That is you can talk about any of them under worst, best, or average. Unless we say something more specific when we talk about any of them we default to talking about them under worst case. That said we pretty much never use  big Œ© and rarely bother to talk about big Œò. The thing that differs in usage from math is that we tend to expect you to talk about the best bound we know.

Author: gcevans#8805
Content: So for example while it is correct in math to say mergesort is O(n!) it is not really useful so we would say that it was wrong if we asked for the running time of mergesort which has a tight bound of O(n log n).

Author: Liseiden#9948
Content:
using CS173 proof structure:
T(n) = T(n-1) + 5
T(n-1) = T(n-2) + 5, substitute into above.
T(n) = T(n-2) + 5 + 5
T(n) = T(n-3) + 5 + 5 + 5
T(n) = T(n-k) + 5k.
Let n-k = 1, then k = n-1.
T(n) = T(1) + 5(n-1)
so T(n) = 1 + 5n - 5 = 5n - 4

Author: gcevans#8805
Content: One way to think about it is that when in CS we say that the running time is big O of something we are saying that it is the best bound we can prove at the time. We rarely use big Œò since so many algorithms have cases that are fast as well as with many algorithms we have not been able to show the tightest bounds.

Author: willyt123#8431
Content: What's the difference between amortized running time and regular running time?

Author: mersaults#1657
Content:
The idea here is that when you're finding the 8th node from the front you **always **have to progress by 8 nodes until you find what you need, regardless of the size of your linked list. In other words, O(8) is always your run time. Formally, O(8) = O(1) since they're both constant terms.

In a singly linked list (meaning you can't progress backwards from a tail node), the size of your problem is scaled by the size of your list. Every single time you find the 8th node from the end, you have to traverse through n - 8 nodes since you can't start from the back, meaning that the total number of nodes you have to traverse is variable. This means that you have O(n) runtime since your runtime scales linearly by the size of your linked list.

Author: sadboiben#2305
Content:
```
Definition of Connected Component (1):
If there exists a path from vertex A to B, then A and B are part of the same connected components

Definition of Path (2):
A path is a walk that does not repeat vertices

Definition of Walk (3):
A walk is an alternating list of vertices and edges that connect them;
```
https://courses.grainger.illinois.edu/cs173/fa2020/Lectures/Notes/DirectedGraphsNotes.pdf

Author: sadboiben#2305
Content: if it were a directed graph, the walk from vertex A to vertex A is given by: `A(A,A)A`

Author: sadboiben#2305
Content: We can take a walk of length 0 (which is allowed by definition), which is just the same vertex `A`

Author: sadboiben#2305
Content: Thus, there exists a walk of length 0 from `A` "to" `A`. There also exists a path because we do not visit the same vertex twice, as our walk is just described as `w = A` (instead of let's say something like `w = A(A,B)B` which goes from vertex A to B)

Author: sadboiben#2305
Content: Thus there `A` is part of the same connected component as itself

Content: i said vacuously true because it could be that there is no edge, so it's its own connected component because the antecedent is false

Author: gcevans#8805
Content: Here is the definition from Prof. Flecks book ```If we have a graph G that might or might not be connected, we can divide G into connected components. Each connected component contains a maximal (i.e. biggest possible) set of nodes that are all connected to one another, plus all their edges```

Author: gcevans#8805
Content: So the set of connected components give a partition of the graph.

Author: gcevans#8805
Content: We often use this idea to split a graph into subgraphs since many algorithms need connectivity to work.

Content: 8 should be the + node's left child because it comes next in the traversal

Author: Ibraheemus#5329
Content: Both 3 and 6 are supposed to be leaf nodes so I know I'm done with this subtree

Author: Ibraheemus#5329
Content: * is the next item in the traversal, since the root node is an asterix I know it still needs its right child

Author: Ibraheemus#5329
Content: so I put * as its right child

Author: Ibraheemus#5329
Content: 9 is next in the traversal,  so it should be *'s left child

Author: Ibraheemus#5329
Content: + is next and I know * need two children, it becomes *'s right child

Author: Ibraheemus#5329

Author: Ibraheemus#5329
Content: - comes next, and since I know +'s have two children and i've already given it a left child, I set - to be +'s right child

Author: justin#4179
Content:
balance < -1, and:
1. left balance < -1 then right
2. left balance > 1 then left right

balance > 1, and:
1. right balance > 1 then left
2. right balance < -1 then right left

Author: anonamause10#8084

Author: PeterYR#8655
Content: Hash tables should generally be a decent bit bigger than the data stored

Author: PeterYR#8655
Content: Otherwise hash collisions can result in really long finds/inserts

Author: PeterYR#8655
Content: In a hash table of 2900 capacity with 2899 UINs already stored, inserting the last one will have to search through half of all of those keys, on average

Author: mm-is-here#1259
Content: why not e, then?

Author: PeterYR#8655
Content: "use no more memory than necessary"

Author: PeterYR#8655
Content: 100k would be pretty fast, but also overkill

Content: Can't see why that would be an issue, if you have 2900 UINs and 2900 slots you should never run until a hash collision right?

Author: anonamause10#8084
Content: I suppose it's possible that UINs still hash collide

Author: mersaults#1657
Content: A table with 2900 UINs is only fine if someone developed a hashing algorithm that guaranteed no collisions

Author: Stea1thTornado#8402
Content: And designing a hash function that guarantees no collisions is theoretically impossible, since you are compressing an infinite input space into a finite output space

Author: gcevans#8805
Content: Also not as we saw in lecture the best load factor was something between .5-.7 assuming SUHA. Less than that not a lot of reductions in collisions but more cost and more than that the collisions start to really spike.

Author: mersaults#1657
Content: No, BFS is O(m+n) for an adjacency list, and O(n^2) for an adjacency matrix.

Author: mersaults#1657
Content: The idea of setting worst case to m = n^2 doesn't work because it's not uniquely the worst case for all graphs that m is n^2 (consider a graph with three vertices and the maximum number of non-redundant edges). Even in the case that you could do that, why not have a worst case of O(n^3) at that point?

Author: mersaults#1657
Content: If you need the intuition for the runtime of the adjacency matrix, remember that the length of the  adjacency matrix for any given vertex will be |V| = n.

Author: willyt123#8431
Content: Can someone help me with this question please? I am not sure how to go about it. Is there a general formula for the number of cross edges?

Author: Hanforallckskyslikcaprifest#1525
Content: and for back edges?

Author: willyt123#8431
Content: yeah

Author: willyt123#8431
Content: I remember a similar question like that too on a previous practice exam

Author: justin#4179
Content: Is the answer 4n+3?

Author: willyt123#8431
Content: Yes!

Author: justin#4179
Content: Here‚Äôs my approach

Author: justin#4179
Content: I recognised that the total number of edges is 5n+2

Author: justin#4179
Content: We note that we would use a minimum of n-1 edges to discover every node in a connected graph

Author: justin#4179
Content: Meaning for any given connected graph, we can use n-1 edges to reach every single node through some path or the other

Author: justin#4179
Content: Then we know that the number of cross edges then is simply the number of edges that don‚Äôt discover a new node

Author: willyt123#8431
Content: Would it be the same for back edges as well?

Author: justin#4179
Content: similar concept, i think i've seen that question before so give me a second to look for it

Author: justin#4179
Content: this one, right?

Author: willyt123#8431
Content: Yeah

Author: justin#4179
Content: yeah, it's the same idea, except they didn't give you the total number of edges

Author: justin#4179
Content: the keywords here then are: connected, undirected, degree 6

Author: justin#4179
Content: because it's undirected and degree 6, the number of edges would hence be 6n/2

Author: justin#4179
Content: since deg * n would count each edge twice (e.g. A->B and A<-B both exist)

Author: justin#4179
Content:
so that gives our total number of edges: 3n
total number of edges we need (discovery edges): n - 1
total number of back edges: (3n) - (n-1) = 2n + 1

Author: willyt123#8431
Content: That was a really good explanation! Thank you so much!

Author: justin#4179
Content: no problem!

Author: willyt123#8431
Content: Do you know how it would change if it were a directed graph?

Author: justin#4179
Content: if it was directed more details would be needed

Author: justin#4179
Content: cause in that case we could not guarantee that for every edge A->B it exists a B->A

Author: justin#4179
Content: it'd be very difficult for us to generally compute how many edges are

Author: willyt123#8431
Content: oh okay thanks

Author: justin#4179
Content: i feel like calculating the back/cross edges would also be a bit less trivial as well

Author: LtZero#3606
Content: the hash function gives the index in the array at which to store the contents

Author: LtZero#3606
Content:
insert 1 -> (3 * 1 + 4) % 7 = 0 -> insert 1 at the 0th index of the array
insert 3 -> (3 * 3 + 4) % 7 = 6 -> insert 3 at 6th index of array
insert 8 -> (3 * 8 + 4) % 7 = 0 -> try to insert 8 at the 0th index, but encounters collision with 1 -> try next index over (linear probing) -> can insert there, 8 inserted at 1st index
and so on

Author: Stea1thTornado#8402
Content: figuring out that (i) and (iii) are true for that hash function is relatively straightforward. Deterministic means that if you take the same input (k in this example) and run it through the hash function multiple times, everytime that specific input will hash to the same value, so (i) is true. Since its just pretty simply math, its easy enough to figure out. Similarly, since the hash function just does a few constant operations, (iii) will be true too.

Author: Johnx#2889
Content: I'm pretty sure the hash function/equation they listed violated (ii) because of the 2k^2 + 2k. You can kind of deduce that the resulting values aren't going to be evenly distributed from 0-9 at all.

Author: Stea1thTornado#8402
Content: formally, uniform distribution means that the probability of some input hashing to some spot in the hash table is 1 / N where N is the size of the hash table

Author: Johnx#2889
Content: 2k^2 + 2k would lead to *only* even numbers for literally any value of k (because of 2 *)

Author: Johnx#2889
Content: so a lot of the indices will just be "left out" (in this case, the odd ones)

Author: Johnx#2889
Content: and since like half (?) of these indices are going to be left out, it doesn't distribute the keys very uniformly across the entire array.

Author: mm-is-here#1259
Johnx#2889
Content: in bfs, you push the source node and all of its neighbors onto the queue at once. So if two nodes are right next to each other on the queue, that could mean two things: 1) node y comes right after you visit node x, so the # of edges/path length is +1 for the second node compared to the first node, or 2) x and y are ***adjacent neighbors***. So # of edges/path length between (s and y) and (s and x) are the same.

Content: Yes, a stack and queue require you to remove every element at worst to find an element

Content: A binary search tree has no promises about its height so it could essentially just be a fancy linked list

Author: justin#4179
Content: So AVL is the only one where you are ensured a balanced tree that allows you to look things up faster
